		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Chiptune synth for DAWs or standalone</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I'm developing a chiptune synths for use in <a href="https://fatony.net/stuff/music/" class="postlink">my music</a>. I've decided to start with emulating NES concept-wise. So I've called my project &quot;fTz NES Synth&quot;. Over the course of my research I've found that there are a lot of things beyond NES so I decided not to confine myself to NES emulation. So I renamed it to &quot;fTz Chiptune&quot;.<br /><br />And today I think is a good time to release the first version of the synth. It emulates most stuff except sweep and some noise quirks.<br /><br />CC 75 controls decay time on all plugins. CC 1 controls duty cycle of pulse wave.<br /><br />I'm a huge free software supporter so I'm releasing a GNU/Linux binaries as this is the only operating system I have. I've built a DSSI, LV2 and VST plugins as well as standalone JACK apps. I've included my other libraries in this release for it to be mostly self-contained. You'll only need libstdc++-6 to run. I currently have only AMD64 build.<br /><br />The core code is written in pure ISO C++14 (+ #pragma once) so porting it to other operating systems is trivial.<br /><br />Website:<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="https://ftz.fatony.net/projects/chiptune/">https://ftz.fatony.net/projects/chiptune/</a><!-- m --><br /><br />Source code:<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="https://gitlab.com/ftz/chiptune">https://gitlab.com/ftz/chiptune</a><!-- m -->

		

		</td>
	</tr>
